Text: That's a wrap!
The last few weeks have been fairly stress-free.
I am extremely grateful that we had an opportunity to undergo a project that was somewhat out of my scope but also very relevant to the data science pathway.
I suppose I would like to take a moment to appreciate that the team was unproblematic.
Everyone conveyed an extent of proactiveness and initiative to do their part in the project and had displayed the enthusiasm to essentially be there.

It was a nice opportunity to polish off these studio projects to see what good communication may look like - especially when comparing from being in a team that was a little too quiet and being in a team that had a lot of tension.
I am at least glad to know that the others in my team enjoyed the project.
However, as always, it would not be self reflection if I did not have self critique's for myself in preparation for internship placements.
Plan.
A recurring theme for all of these projects is somewhat a sense of unease.
At the end of the day - it somehow always boils down to the lack of planning.
Truthfully, part of this actually means to spend quality time researching and understanding the process down to the bone.
I also need to find a more effective way to 'plan' - and understand what planning really means to me.
I think beingÂ hard on myself to understand the process deeply is a way to drive me to put in 110% of my energy.
Funnily enough, I found myself relating to the women from the past Shift cohort when they said doing Shift was all or nothing.
This was because they had a family to raise or had sacrificed something to be here.

I don't have kids nor did I have to sacrifice anything to be here - but I guess the all or nothing stems from the fact that this whole experience feels like a second chance to prove myself - to myself - it is essentially all or nothing.
Sorry, I just went waaay off topic.
Point being is that I need to have a plan of action to understand the project deeply at the initiation phase of the project.
Positive.
Maybe it's just me, or maybe it is a girl thing - but as you can tell - I found it difficult to be satisfied with our 'accomplishments'.
In this project - point blank, everyone enjoyed the project, was proactive, the progress went fairly smoothly and we had a fairly cohesive team.
That alone should be a positive celebratory factor - which it is!
However, it is clear that I need to work on celebrating the small wins in life and just going with the flow.
Perhaps it is a process of trusting the process and just conveying some positivity to help put my mind at ease.
The team was amazing and I am eternally grateful for having the opportunity to work with a handful of very talented human beings.
To conclude, I think the studio projects were a great opportunity to understand what real life projects are like.
This past project was awesome and Jeremiah was an awesome client to work with.
For a future note to myself - as I have said previously - "discomfort is an opportunity for personal growth".
I am constantly uncomfortable so something must be going right.

Teacher2, thank you heaps for your support and effort into helping the team and I.  I am sure you are sick of reading about me ranting about random stuff - I'll try to be more positive in the future hehe.
Also, I think you have a good speaking tone.
It may not be 'textbook' diplomatic, but it is still a very respectable tone ;) Alright, have a great rest of your day!
Overall
